# rust-url
[![Build status](https://img.gs/czjpqfbdkz/full/https://github.com/servo/rust-url/workflows/CI/badge.svg)](https://github.com/servo/rust-url/actions?query=workflow%3ACI) [![Coverage](https://img.gs/czjpqfbdkz/full/https://codecov.io/gh/servo/rust-url/branch/master/graph/badge.svg)](https://codecov.io/gh/servo/rust-url) [![Chat](https://img.shields.io/badge/chat-%23rust--url:mozilla.org-%2346BC99?logo=Matrix)](https://matrix.to/#/#rust-url:mozilla.org) [![License: MIT](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-blue.svg)](https://github.com/servo/rust-url/blob/797b2e2a0a31ffd75a004efac859618a634d5fa4/url/LICENSE-MIT) [![License: Apache 2.0](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-Apache%202.0-blue.svg)](https://github.com/servo/rust-url/blob/797b2e2a0a31ffd75a004efac859618a634d5fa4/url/LICENSE-APACHE)
URL library for Rust, based on the [URL Standard](https://url.spec.whatwg.org/).
[Documentation](https://docs.rs/url)
Please see [UPGRADING.md](https://github.com/servo/rust-url/blob/main/UPGRADING.md) if you are upgrading from a previous version.
## Alternative Unicode back ends
``url`` depends on the ``idna`` crate. By default, ``idna`` uses [ICU4X](https://github.com/unicode-org/icu4x/) as its Unicode back end. If you wish to opt for different tradeoffs between correctness, run-time performance, binary size, compile time, and MSRV, please see the [README of the latest version of the ``idna_adapter`` crate](https://docs.rs/crate/idna_adapter/latest) for how to opt into a different Unicode back end.
#### Dependencies
~2–3MB  ~53K SLoC
  * [form_urlencoded](https://lib.rs/crates/form_urlencoded "1.2.1")[+alloc](https://lib.rs/crates/form_urlencoded/features#feature-alloc)
  * [idna](https://lib.rs/crates/idna "1.0.3")[+alloc](https://lib.rs/crates/idna/features#feature-alloc)[+compiled_data](https://lib.rs/crates/idna/features#feature-compiled_data)
  * [percent-encoding](https://lib.rs/crates/percent-encoding "2.3.1")[+alloc](https://lib.rs/crates/percent-encoding/features#feature-alloc)
  * [ optional ](https://lib.rs/crates/url/features#feature-serde "serde is optional feature") [serde](https://lib.rs/crates/serde "1.0")[+derive](https://lib.rs/crates/serde/features#feature-derive)


  * dev  [bencher](https://lib.rs/crates/bencher "0.1")
  * dev  [serde_json](https://lib.rs/crates/serde_json "1.0")
  * dev  [wasm-bindgen-test](https://lib.rs/crates/wasm-bindgen-test "0.3") wasm32 unknown


#### [Other features](https://lib.rs/crates/url/features)

enriched_crate.readme_summary: The `url` crate is a Rust implementation of the [URL Standard](https://url.spec.whatwg.org/), enabling robust parsing, manipulation, and serialization of URLs. It supports extracting and modifying URL components, handling relative URLs with base resolution, and includes optional features like `serde` for serialization/deserialization and `debugger_visualizer` for enhanced debugging in Visual Studio. Additionally, it offers `no_std` support via the `alloc` feature and re-exports utilities like `form_urlencoded` for working with URL-encoded data.
enriched_crate.factual_counterfactual:
### Pair 1: Serde Integration  
✅ **Factual**: The `url` crate supports serialization and deserialization of `Url` objects when the `serde` feature is enabled, allowing seamless integration with data formats like JSON.  
❌ **Counterfactual**: The `url` crate includes `serde` support by default, without requiring the `serde` feature to be explicitly enabled.  

---

### Pair 2: Debugger Visualizer  
✅ **Factual**: Enabling the `debugger_visualizer` feature in the `url` crate adds a natvis file for Visual Studio, providing enhanced debugging views for `Url` objects, but requires Rust 1.71 or later.  
❌ **Counterfactual**: The `debugger_visualizer` feature in the `url` crate adds debugging support for all IDEs, including IntelliJ and VS Code, without any additional configuration.  

---

### Pair 3: Default Features  
✅ **Factual**: Starting from version 2.5.3, the `url` crate has the `std` feature enabled by default, which provides standard library support. Versions prior to 2.5.3 had no default features.  
❌ **Counterfactual**: The `url` crate has always included the `std` feature by default, regardless of the version.
